  "chunk_index": 38,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot concludes that Robin Upward murdered his mother, Mrs. Upward. Poirot notes that the killer's arrogance and the deliberate arrangement of \"props\" at the crime scene allowed the murder to occur even though Mrs. Oliver was nearby. Following this revelation, Poirot confronts Miss Williams, discovering that she is actually Maud Craig, the daughter of Eve Kane. Maud explains that she had sought revenge after learning that Eve Kane had not died in Australia as believed, but had instead become the wealthy and arrogant Mrs. Upward. Maud had taken a job to investigate and had gone to the house with a gun to confront her mother, only to find Mrs. Upward already dead. Poirot decides not to take legal action against her.\n\nIn an epilogue, Poirot and Superintendent Spence celebrate the resolution of the case at a restaurant. Spence observes that Robin Upward's confession was facilitated by his own cowardice and a lack of evidence. They discuss various local figures, including Mrs. Carpenter, whose past as a cabaret dancer led her to hide her true status, and the Weatherby family, whose conflicts are driven by money. Poirot reveals he is meddling in the lives of Dierdre Henderson and James Bentley in hopes of arranging their marriage. The conversation shifts to Dr. Lund, whom Spence reveals was once accused of poisoning his first wife via anonymous letters. Poirot realizes this explains why Dr. Lund attempted to push him under a train at the station, as the doctor feared Poirot was investigating him. Spence confirms that Robin Upward will be tried for murder the following week.",
